A black box in your car?
While highway planners in the United States struggle to find the money to fix decaying highway infrastructure, many see a solution in the form of a small black box that attaches to the dashboard of your car.
The devices, which record every mile a driver drives and relay the information to officials, are the focus of a controversial attempt in Washington and government planning offices to overhaul the outdated system of funding major U.S. highways.
The generally uninteresting aspect of the planning of the major axes has suddenly provoked a lively debate and heated alliances.
Libertarians have joined with environmental groups to lobby the government to use the little boxes to keep track of the miles you drive, and potentially the road you drive on, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The Tea Party has landed.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses its concern about the protection of privacy.
And while members of Congress can't agree on whether to proceed, several states have not waited.
They're looking at how, over the next decade, they can move to a system where drivers pay based on the number of miles they drive.
Thousands of motorists have already taken these black boxes, sometimes equipped with GPS-based monitoring, on an experimental trip.
This is really necessary for our nation.
"It's not like we have a choice", said Hasan Ikhrata, executive director of the Southern California Association of Governments, which plans for the state to begin recording the miles driven by every Californian by 2025.
There's going to be a change in the way we pay these taxes.
The technology is there to do that.
The pressure comes from the fact that the nation's Highway Trust Fund, funded by the taxes Americans pay at the pump, is financially dry.
Americans don't buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars can go more miles with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents a gallon, hasn't been raised in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax, even by one cent, while gasoline prices are high.
 The gas tax is simply unsustainable , said Lee Munnich, a transport policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed tracking devices on 500 cars to test a mileage-based payment system.
'This is proving to be the most logical alternative in the long term,' he said.
Wonks calls this a mileage-based user charge.
It is not surprising that the idea appeals to urban liberals, since the taxes could be used to change driving habits in ways that reduce congestion and emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to achieve the goals set out in the state's ambitious global warming laws.
But Rep. Bill Shuster (R-Pa.), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he also sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
Free market advocates at the Reason Foundation also like the idea of charging drivers per mile.
"This is not just a tax plunging into a big black hole", said Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits that are provided to them.
The move is also supported by two former US Transportation secretaries who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to move in the direction of mileage payments.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have involved about 10,000 cars.
But the House presidency killed the proposal, responding to the concerns of rural lawmakers representing voters who must travel many miles every day to get to work or to the city.
Nevertheless, several states and major cities are making progress on their own.
The most determined is Oregon, which has mobilized 5,000 drivers to conduct the country's largest experiment.
These motorists will soon be paying the state mileage charges instead of gasoline taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is considering one.
Illinois is trying a trial on a limited number of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transportation in states along the U.S. East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida) is looking at how it could implement change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer motorists recently fitted their cars with a camera, drivers were concerned that the government could be tracking their every move.
"Concerns about Big Brother and things like that are a big problem", said Alauddin Khan, who heads performance management strategy at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It's not something people want.
From the beginning of the trial, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website:  It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into full-fledged tracking devices. 
There is no need to build a huge, bulky technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people's daily comings and goings.
Nevada is one of the few states that is now scrambling to find affordable technology that would allow the state to know how many miles a car has driven, but without knowing the exact time or place.
If we can do that, Khan added, citizens will feel more comfortable.
The search for this technology has led some state agencies to call on a small California start-up called True Mileage.
The original purpose of the society was not to help motorists who pay taxes to the states.
It was looking to break into the emerging auto insurance market, where drivers would pay based on their mileage.
But the devices she's testing have caught the eye of the major planners because they don't use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, periodically downloaded by modem.
"People will be more likely to do this if you don't track their speed and location", said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
There have been serious mistakes in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are much less expensive and less intrusive ways of doing this.
In Oregon, planners are trying the experiment by giving motorists different choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They can still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a flat fee based on the average number of miles driven by all residents of the state.
Other states hope to sell the concept to wary citizens by allowing devices to do more, rather than less.
In New York City, transportation officials are looking to develop a taxation device that would also be equipped to pay for parking fees, provide insurance  pay to drive  and create a set of real-time speed data from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
 Motorists would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits the system offers them , said an urban planning document.
However, some transport planners wonder if the whole debate on mileage payments is just a huge distraction.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission in the San Francisco Bay Area, officials say Congress could very easily handle the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by raising taxes on gasoline.
A one-off or annual supplementary tax could be imposed on drivers of hybrid vehicles and others whose vehicles do not consume much gasoline, so that everyone pays his fair share.
 There is no need for radical surgery when you just need aspirin, said Randy Rentschler, the commission's director of legislation and public affairs.
