But ever since whistle-blower-turned-consultant Edward Snowden began revealing his endless treasure trove of information about U.S. surveillance secrets, European governments and business leaders have been wondering whether to believe the whistle-blower.
Reports that the US National Security Agency spied on Brazilian oil company Petrobras and gained access to data held by US cloud storage service providers, including Google and Yahoo, have fuelled business paranoia about state surveillance more than ever.
The revelation that German Chancellor Angela Merkel's phone had been hacked, perhaps for a decade, was the last straw.
