Germany has become the first European nation to recognize a third gender for infants born with ambiguous sex organs.
The gender of newborn children will no longer be rigidly assigned at birth.
Under the new law, parents will no longer be required to declare the gender of their child, allowing them to write an  undetermined  or  unspecified  on their birth certificate.
The purpose of the law was to remove the pressure on parents who may be making hasty decisions about sex reassignment surgery for their infants, and to combat discrimination against intersex people.
According to the BBC, an intersex person would have said years later, "I'm neither a man nor a woman".
I'll be the patchwork the doctors created, bruised and bruised.
It is estimated that one in every 2,000 children born each year is neither a boy nor a girl.
They are intersexed, intersexuality being one of the group of sixty or so diseases diagnosed as disorders of sexual development, a generic term for people with atypical chromosomes or gonads (ovaries or testicles) or abnormally developed sexual organs.
Wallis Simpson could have been intersex.
Sex identification is still not well understood, but most experts in the United States say that when sex cannot be determined, it is best to use the best available information to assign it, and then wait and monitor the child's psychological and physical development before considering surgery, if necessary.
Dr. Jack Drescher, a New York psychiatrist and sexuality expert, said that the new German law  seems like a good idea .
Intersex children pose an ethical dilemma.
 Some people suffer from extremely serious illnesses that require surgery, but this is not the case for most children, he added.
It's possible to do a sex assignment without surgery, and see how the identity develops.
The science of how a child will develop a sexual identity is not very precise.
No one can answer the question of why this is happening.
It's like the mystery that surrounds gay people.
A report submitted to the European Commission in 2011 described intersex people as different from transsexual or transgender people, since their status is not linked to gender but rather to their biological constitution, which is neither exclusively that of a man nor exclusively that of a woman, but is generally both at the same time and not clearly defined as either.
These characteristics may manifest themselves in secondary sex characteristics (such as muscle mass, hair, chest and height), primary sex characteristics (such as reproductive and sexual organs) or chromosome structure and hormones.
The report also provided an overview of discrimination faced by intersex and transgender people in employment, as well as the scale of harassment and violence and prejudice-motivated crimes.
Young boys who are gender non-conforming now have camps that are specifically for them.
