Historically, children born without male or female sex organs were called hermaphrodites, after the name of the magnificent Greek god who had both sexes.
And it was only a decade ago that the medical community saw gender as a piece of slate that could be erased and redrawn.
But now, many are questioning the ethical basis of surgery, knowing that gender identity is complex and that doctors can sometimes get it wrong, not knowing how a child will feel about their sex reassignment when they grow up.
 In the mid-20th century, this was called a psychiatric emergency , Drescher said.
When these kids were born, we didn't call the psychiatrist, we called the surgeon.
The dominant theory on how to treat children with ambiguous sex organs was pioneered by Dr. John Money of Johns Hopkins University, who considered gender to be malleable.
He coined the term  gender identity and argued that social and environmental cues  how parents raise a child  interact with a child's genes and hormones to shape it so that it is identified as male or female.
But in a 1966 case known as  John/Joan , his theories gave rise to controversy.
He had advised the parents of a boy whose penis had been cut off in a botched circumcision to have him castrated entirely, with his testicles removed, and to raise him as a girl.
 Money presented this as a successful transition case, but it was not the case, Drescher said.
At about 15 years of age, he became a boy again and married a woman.
But at 38, he killed himself.
