George Kerevan: The break-up of Europe gives the Scots a choice
Another day, another disturbing story of independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland would be required to join the European free-trade area in order to join the EU.
And now we hear stories of passport control at Berwick and a border of barbed wire along Hadrian's Wall.
While it is true that the Strathclyde newspaper has pointed out the possible economic benefits of greater freedom of movement with the rest of Europe, it was not in the headlines (and it was to be expected).
Nor did anyone say that the EU member states spend a lot of their time circumventing their formal rules when it suits them.
Since Scotland is not part of the Schengen area at the moment, continued non-compliance would be a small concession that Brussels could offer in return for all that it wants to get from the Scots.
So this is a story that is not a story.
And a story so old that it is now frozen: I first heard the myth that independence means passport controls more than 40 years ago.
Yet, an interesting point has been overlooked in this interpretation of a dusty old tale.
Why should an independent Scotland follow the instructions of Europe, really?
Why trade the London yoke for the Brussels yoke, especially now?
The real news about Europe is that the great post-war plan to unify Europe has come to a standstill.
With the euro crisis, the Europe Project is officially dead.
Across Europe, parties opposed to the EU or advocating the abandonment of the euro as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party, founded only this year and coming out of nowhere, gathered almost five million votes in the September federal elections and pulled the Liberal Democratic Party (the equivalent of our Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been national opposition to the idea of a federal Europe.
However, the recent economic crisis has marked a turning point.
The austerity imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, combined with the strain on national economies through membership of the single currency, has led many to think that the Europe Project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments running excessive budget deficits - this was true only of Greece.
The European system has instead imposed on its members exchange rates favourable to German exporters - which German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluing the national currency, the southern European countries are faced with an inherent productivity problem vis-√†-vis Germany.
The only way out is to make the deep cuts in wages and public spending that Berlin has encouraged.
Beyond the current budgetary and monetary problems, there is a deeper malaise about productivity in Europe.
Following the green  energy policies imposed by Brussels  which are a reason to subsidize French and German companies in the energy sector at the expense of the consumer  European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas as the United States.
This is a cost-defying disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
The European petrochemical industry will not be prevented by all the wage freezes in the world from being penalized by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, the revolt is raging, especially in France, one of the EU's major leaders.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a passport of its political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy on Europe, leaving the French economy to scramble.
The result: Marine Le Pen's far-right, anti-European National Front party has just won a crucial by-election, sending the ruling Socialists back to third place.
The National Front is now the most popular party in France with 24% of the vote - a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split on the right will automatically favour the left.
What is Marine Le Pen doing with her newfound popularity with the French white working class?
It wants to use next year's European elections to create an anti-single currency and anti-European bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-European parties make a good showing in these elections, which is very possible, such a bloc could control the European Parliament for the first time.
I think that very soon anti-European and anti-single currency sentiment in Europe will unite and eventually kill the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will return to something more like the free Europe of (sovereign) nations favoured by General de Gaulle.
Germany and a few of its satellite economies may retain the euro, but France and southern Europe will have their own currencies.
I expect the UK to distance itself from this project, and I hope it will look kindly upon the United States.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left behind in the Atlantic.
What about Scotland?
We can decide to be a region of (essentially) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which includes sending people to Berlin and Brussels.
I believe that Scotland could settle for a freer European agreement provided we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries would be easier in a non-federal Europe of Nations.
Otherwise we should follow Norway's example and maintain our economic independence.
The SNP government of Scotland is  and is notably  the most successful anti-austerity political movement in Europe, having won a spectacular majority in 2011 based on its opposition to the deep cuts proposed (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor Alistair Darling and the Conservative/Liberal Democrat coalition that followed.
It would be ridiculous now for Scotland to vote for independence if it means accepting the austerity imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: Aging earlier
Studies show that African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than white girls.
Physical changes do not mean puberty is imminent
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts believe the obesity epidemic may be a trigger for early puberty
The tendency for early puberty is not as pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in family and child health issues.
Does a mother have to worry if her daughter's breasts and pubic hair start growing at seven or eight?
At the annual meeting of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, Dr. Paul Kaplowitz, a pediatric endocrinologist, explained that these early physical changes are quite common among young Americans and represent a new norm.
 I spend a lot of time reassuring parents  in general, this does not indicate a rapid evolution towards full puberty , said Kaplowitz.
Obvious signs of development, such as breast growth, underarm and pubic hair, and body odors, appear earlier in girls.
But there's been only a slight advance in the age of first menstruation over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12 and a half years, up from 12 years old in 1970.
 Once the breast has begun to develop, it takes at least two or three years before the first menstrual periods appear , said Kaplowitz, also the author of  Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem .
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty will evolve.
There is debate as to what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but it is considered  premature  when breast development is accompanied by sudden growth before the age of 8 years.
In most cases, development slows or stops - something a pediatrician can monitor closely.
A faster progression may warrant tests by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
Treatments exist to delay the onset of menstruation and prevent other consequences: premature bone ageing that can stunt growth and small stature in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug and hormone therapy are based on the child's age, developmental rate, growth rate and emotional maturity.
The psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about medication but acknowledges that  controlling puberty can mitigate some behavioral problems and the feeling for young girls to be different from others .
The other big problem is understandable: Parents simply don't want their very young girls to have their periods.
 They fear the risk of pregnancy or even how they will handle hygiene issues , said Kaplowitz.
"It was a shock", recalls a woman whose 10-year-old daughter got her first period.
Even though there were signs and we had talked about the period, she wasn't emotionally prepared.
She came home from school scared and upset to be the first among her friends.
There are many theories about the causes of precocious puberty.
Yet, there is no consistent theory that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz says the most credible hypothesis is that obesity is an epidemic.
He was involved in a study of girls aged 6 to 9 years that linked body fat percentage to the onset of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other influential factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than white girls.
There are various explanations.
Globally, the mechanisms of early puberty seem to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genetics.
Another problem: Although boys have younger facial and pubic hair, the tendency toward true precocious puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference emphasized the complexity of the subject.
Acne and pubic hair are common, even in infants and toddlers.
 We need to be careful about how we identify the true onset of puberty , said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at the Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to consult their pediatrician about how to communicate with their child.
"It may mean having a conversation earlier than expected", Kaplowitz explained.
If you remain calm, your child will generally respond well.
Girls who have premature puberty need to be reassured that, even when it happens sooner than expected, the process is a part of life.
