New anti-nicotine vaccine could take away the fun of smoking
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could suppress the pleasure of smoking a cigarette.
A single dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice from lifelong nicotine addiction.
More tests are needed before human trials can begin, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said the early signs were encouraging.
"We really hope that this kind of vaccine strategy can help the millions of smokers who have tried to quit, exhausting every method available on the market today, but find that their addiction is strong enough to overcome these different approaches", said Professor Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to carry the genetic information necessary to design anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then begin to produce a steady stream of antibodies.
Antibodies target any nicotine molecules in the bloodstream and neutralize them before they reach the brain, thus preventing the smoker from getting his dose of nicotine.
In tests, vaccinated mice that were then given nicotine continued their normal activity.
But the mice that had not been vaccinated  were appeased , the researchers said, a sign that nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous vaccines against tobacco have proven ineffective because they contained antibodies.
The injections had to be repeated so frequently to keep the antibody levels high that they were too costly and inconvenient.
But the cost of the new vaccine should be much lower because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if the future vaccine for human use was completely safe, it could be administered to children before they were tempted to try a cigarette, thus preventing any nicotine addiction.
But it's more likely to be used by smokers who want to quit.
 They will know that if they start smoking again, they will not enjoy it because of the nicotine vaccine, and this can help them to lose their bad habit , he added.
British scientists said the findings were interesting but pointed out that much more research was needed.
