FAA: Air passengers can now use gadgets on board planes (but not make a call with their mobile phone)
Airline passengers will be able to use their door-to-door electronic devices to read, work, play games, watch movies and listen to music - but not talk on their cell phones - under highly anticipated new guidelines released Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration.
But passengers should not expect immediate changes.
The speed with which the change will be implemented will vary from airline to airline, FAA Administrator Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
Airlines will have to prove to the FAA that their aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated crew training manuals and aircraft stowage rules to be compliant.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of electronic devices on their aircraft.
Delta and JetBlue are among the airlines that have already submitted plans.
Depending on the plan, we may approve the expanded use of electronic devices very soon", the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers must turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the aircraft doors are closed.
They're not supposed to turn them on until the plane reaches 10,000 feet and the captain gives the go-ahead.
Passengers are supposed to turn off their devices when descending from the plane before landing and not turn them on again until the plane has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines with aircraft properly protected from electronic interference will be able to allow passengers to use their aircraft during takeoffs, landings and ground handling, the FAA said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft that have been modified so that passengers can use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Association of Professional Flight Attendants, said she was happy about the changes.
"Once the new policy is safely implemented and we will work closely with the carriers to make it work, it will be profitable for everyone", Glading said in a statement.
We are frankly tired of feeling like  hall controllers when it comes to this issue.
But it will still be forbidden to connect to the internet to surf, exchange emails and text messages or download data below 10,000 feet, the agency said.
Passengers will be required to put their smartphones, tablets and other devices into airplane mode.
So still no Words With Friends, the Scrabble-style online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he was loudly ejected from an American Airlines flight after refusing to turn off his device while it was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices like laptops will always need to be stowed away because they could hurt someone if they flew through the cabin.
Mobile phones will also continue to be prohibited on board.
The regulatory power regarding cell phones belongs to the Federal Communications Commission and not the FAA.
The FAA may lift the ban on certain electronic devices during takeoff and landing.
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national expert on transportation safety, said on CBS News that cell phones were still considered a risk.
"Cell phones are really a problem, not only because they could potentially create interference with navigation instruments, but because we know, from the FCC, that they could disrupt cell phone relay antennas if used on board", Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to look into the problem recommended last month that the government allow wider use of personal electronic devices.
Pressure on the FAA has increased in recent years to loosen restrictions on their use.
Critics such as Senator Claire McCaskill, D-Mo., argue that there is no valid security reason for these bans.
Restrictions are also becoming more difficult to enforce as the use of the devices has become pervasive.
Some studies indicate that at least one third of passengers forget to turn off their devices or do so deliberately.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices in 1996 following reports of interference with navigation and communication instruments when passengers carried FM radios, the high-tech gadget of the day.
New airliners rely much more on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed to withstand electronic interference and approved by the FAA.
Airlines have been allowing their passengers to use Wi-Fi at cruising altitudes for several years.
Aircraft modified to accommodate Wi-Fi systems also have better resistance to interference.
The vast majority of airliners should allow for wider use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today's electronic devices generally emit radio signals of much lower power than previous generations of devices.
Electronic book readers, for example, emit only minimal transmissions when a page is turned.
But the transmissions are stronger when devices are downloading or sending data.
Amazon.com is among those pushing for a relaxation of restrictions on passenger use of electronic devices.
In 2011, the company executives loaded a plane with Kindle e-book readers and flew it to see if there were any problems, but there were none.
This has inspired members of the FAA advisory committee with mixed feelings about whether or not the use of the aircraft presents a risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believed the interference from the aircraft was real, even if the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said that there are only anecdotal reports from pilots that the devices can interfere with aircraft systems, and most of them are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to ask passengers to turn off their aircraft during instrument landings in low visibility conditions.
