How biometrics will invade our lives
No more passwords to access her smartphone or pay for her groceries?
Researchers in the United States, France and Japan predict a future in which we will be recognized by biometric sensors in phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, deputy director general of Morpho, even believes that "the century will be biometric".
Only biometrics will ensure the identity of a person making transactions in a transversal and transnational universe such as the Internet.
Privacy organizations acknowledge this biometric craze, but are concerned.
In 2011 alone, the French National Commission for Information and Freedoms approved 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, hand shapes or hand veins in companies, administrations, canteens...
"Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere and anytime", says Justin Brookman, consumer privacy officer at the Center for Democracy and Technology in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism in some and pessimism in others?
Biometrics will be based on new technologies, which will enable new services to be provided to citizens and consumers.
Today, the most widely used biometric data in France are fingerprints, the contour of the hand and the network of veins of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its limitations.
"For example, some concrete workers have very badly damaged fingers and their fingerprints are illegible", says Philippe Robin, technical director of the identity area at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection and the verification of the network of veins and the contour of the hand assume a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
This is both a security - you cannot capture this data without their knowledge - and a disadvantage: the procedure sometimes has to be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been carried out for some 20 years on other approaches, such as face recognition and iris (the colored part of the eye).
With the increase in the precision of sensors and the computational power of computers needed to analyze data, these techniques are becoming operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has increased tenfold in the last five years, calculates Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture's R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the UK and the Netherlands have deployed automated border crossings using facial recognition.
It's now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
"Today we are doing research on speech recognition or gait recognition using sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment", says Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at Intel Labs.
As a unique and unmistakable marker, DNA also raises hopes and worries.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered as the ultimate biometric data", confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, director of studies, innovation and prospects at the CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very time-consuming and very expensive.
NEC is offering the police a suitcase worth 90,000 euros to analyse DNA samples at the scene of a crime in one hour.
The uses of biometrics fall into two groups: identification (recognizing a person among others) and authentication (ensuring that the person is who he claims to be).
The identification process has so far involved the issuing of identity papers: biometric data (fingerprints, photograph, iris) must be compared with the information the State has on all citizens already registered.
This ensures that a person does not attempt to impersonate another.
This principle of comparison can have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or a store.
"We retrieve the images from the surveillance cameras and compare them to the photos of celebrities that circulate freely on the Internet", explains Dany Nassif, responsible, at NEC France, for commercial development for biometric identification solutions.
Other uses include taking a picture of a quidam standing in a queue in a store, tracking its progress through facial recognition and calculating the waiting time.
Authentication originally concerned physical accesses (border, protected premises, canteens, etc.) or logical accesses (opening a computer).
More recently, attendance control has been added.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of a friend pointing to another", explains Cyril Bataller of Accenture.
But, increasingly, authentication will also affect transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some ATMs by inserting your card and placing your hand on a biometric reader - this gesture replaces the secret code.
A similar technique is being tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoul√™me by Natural Security in partnership with banks and retailers: when paying in stores with a credit card, the customer does not type in his code, but inserts his finger into a vein scanner.
The experiment is planned to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon be available in French shops.
Some clues to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics attractive to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
"If biometrics can reduce a customer's time at the checkout by 30 seconds, that's a good thing", says the manager of a large store.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you customized options.
Finally, reassure them by highlighting the precautions taken to protect the databases.
"Fingerprints are stored on a first server; people's identities are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which locks if you try to move it", says Philippe Robin, of Thales.
But, in the absence of extensive studies, it is impossible to know whether these speeches really convince users.
Privacy experts, however, continue to worry.
"The advances in facial recognition, the proliferation of surveillance cameras, and the sheer volume of photos available on Facebook, Flickr, and Picasa make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance", predicts Andrew Patrick of the Office of the Privacy Commissioner in Canada.
