Scientists have recently uncovered a link between the movements of a dog's tail and its mood.
Previous studies had found that happy dogs wagged their tails more to the right (from the dog's perspective), while nervous dogs wagged their tails more to the left.
But now scientists say dogs can detect these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: "Everyone knows that in humans, the left and right sides of the brain are involved differently in the stimuli that evoke positive or negative emotions.
Here, we tried to see what was happening in other species.
He added that just as in humans, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the disorderly tail movements of other dogs, researchers followed animals as they watched movies that featured other dogs.
They measured the animals' heart rate and analyzed their behavior.
It probably won't take long before we understand why their tails sometimes go one way and sometimes the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained:  We presented to dogs films with other dogs  either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other confusion factor  and we were able to manipulate the movement of the tail and present it as going more to the left or right. 
When the animals saw an expressionless dog wagging its tail to the right (from the perspective of the dog wagging its tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail that was mostly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog wagging its tail), their heart rate spiked and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not believe that the dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
Rather, he thinks that dogs know by experience which movements they should or should not worry about.
He added:  If you meet other dogs repeatedly and you notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail to the side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react according to this experience. 
The researchers say that the findings could help pet owners, veterinarians, and trainers better understand their pets' emotions.
Dog behaviourist John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at the University of Bristol's School of Veterinary Science, said that this was not the first study to examine the importance of left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team at the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they look at an aggressive dog and to the right when they look at a happy dog.
And in another scientific study by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said:  Dogs were more likely to approach a robot dog when its tail was wagging left rather than right, rather than becoming anxious  the opposite of what was shown in the Italian study. 
He indicated that the differences may be due to the fact that the dogs in the different studies did not fully consider the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could be useful, he explained.
 Although there is a lot of evidence in different mammals that the two sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details are still to be worked out  and dogs are no exception , he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviour can be recorded, it probably won't take long before we understand why their tails sometimes move to one side and sometimes to the other.
