The memory of the 2008 Obama campaign is a sad reminder of what could have happened
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year medical student at Harvard Medical School.
I'm reading a terribly sad book these days.
It's a book that I thought would encourage me through the gloom of my second year of medical school and give me hope.
It's called  The Audacity to Win  and it's a memoir of Barack Obama's 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish my patients' medical reports at night and go to bed, this book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions of people and speeches could take your breath away.
The election ended in a landslide victory and the news anchors took time to reflect on the historic nature of the moment.
My classmates were crying with joy, and my parents kept all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was moving toward the White House and the nation was ready for change.
During Obama's transition period before he took office in 2008, he had 82 percent favorable opinions.
And then I close the book.
Coming back to the present is a difficult awakening, it's like coming out of a dream.
It is hard to remember those days of optimism, they are like distant memories, a sad reminder of past opportunities.
The change really happened in the years after I voted for the first time.
It was nothing like what I had imagined.
I credit Obama with great achievements, from passing the Affordable Care Act to the departure of our military from Iraq, to the end of the "never seen nor known" and the killing of Osama bin Laden.
Furthermore, I believe that partisan obstructionism has destroyed too many efforts to move our nation forward in the areas of immigration reform, public health care and the closing of Guantanamo, among other things.
But after repeatedly defending the Obama administration to my peers and colleagues, I can't come up with any explanations.
I'm on the verge of political despair.
Republican obstructionism cannot explain the wiretapping of foreign leaders, nor the drone attacks on innocent foreign children.
She can't explain the National Security Agency's collection of Americans' private data, or the indictment of whistleblowers who expose government wrongdoing.
It cannot justify the murder of Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, without a trial, nor the evasion of public funding and the overspending during presidential campaigns.
She can't justify the conclusions of a report that says the White House's efforts to silence the media are the most aggressive since the Nixon administration.
And, more recently, she can't excuse not being able to design a simple website for more than three years after the Affordable Care Act was ratified.
I don't know if this is what I expected.
If, at 18, I was supposed to understand that governance could contradict the political campaigns that preceded it.
Of course, the electoral function is unpredictable, because the opposition political party and random events, like the Newton massacre, influence our public conversation.
However, all the examples I have listed above seem to be largely the choice of the administration.
That's what bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a confusing and unrefined alternative that seemed to have no basis for his policies or positions.
I felt that Obama, elected to a second term, free from the pressure of future elections, would deliver on the promises we've heard so much about for so long.
Yet, with the approval rating dropping below 45% this week, it's even harder to go back to 2008 in this book.
It makes me wish for the many promises that have flown by.
This week, I read the part of the book that described how Obama suffered a huge loss to Clinton in the Pennsylvania primary.
At a post-campaign meeting, he told his team that they needed to get back on track and stay true to their cause.
 I want us to focus on our talent, he said.
We must remember who we are.
Five years later, Mr President, I no longer agree with you.
The views expressed in this commentary are solely those of Nathaniel Morris.
