A team of biologists led by the New York-based Wildlife Conservation Society has identified a new species of humpback dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, a scientist at the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Animals and Marine Life (OCEAMM), reports on this discovery for L'Express and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Are you surprised by the discovery of this new species of humpbacked dolphin?
That's good news, but it doesn't surprise me much.
Whereas in the past species were described and identified on the basis of morphology, anatomy and geography, today the development of new tools such as genetics allows us to improve our knowledge of the science of species classification.
It is not impossible that advances in genetics and molecular biology will call into question the classification of species into a genus, a family, or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals based on the morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these classifications are being challenged by advances in genetic science.
Similarly, two very morphologically related species have been distinguished through genetics.
This is the case with the newly identified species.
About a decade ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily - the Pacific humpback dolphins and the Atlantic humpback whales.
Recent analyses have identified four species.
Why is this a significant discovery, as the Wildlife Conservation Society has claimed?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences in order to protect the species and therefore its genetic variability.
Although this population had been known to researchers for a long time, they did not know that it was part of a new species, found only in this area.
So if a problem of mass mortality caused by a viral epidemic or by accidental capture arises in the region, we may be dealing with the extinction of a species, rather than a local disappearance of a population of a species more widely distributed on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered threatened or endangered based on the number of individuals on Earth, i.e. the stock, and the possibility that it has to re-establish itself from the neighbouring stocks.
As for the species Sousa chinensis, from which the population of the newly discovered species is derived, its stock has automatically become smaller, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats, where there is a lot of genetic exchange between populations and individuals.
This gene mixing limits the creation of new species.
Conversely, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
It should be noted that the marine environment is the least well known environment.
We'd rather send robots to Mars than find out what's living in the Marianas Trench, which is only seven miles below the surface of the sea.
We spend more money on the search for life on other planets than we do on marine research, and it's time that changed.
RBS suspends two traders in the foreign exchange market
The Royal Bank of Scotland has suspended two traders from its foreign exchange division according to two sources familiar with the matter, once again showing that the global investigation by regulators into suspected currency market manipulation is beginning to bear fruit.
Some of the world's largest banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank and RBS, have confirmed that they are cooperating with regulators in their investigations of the world's largest financial market, where 5.3 trillion US dollars change hands every day.
The two traders are the first RBS employees to be suspended as part of the expanded investigation that echoes the Libor interbank rate manipulation scandal.
The bank, which declined to comment on the suspensions, confirmed this month that it had received requests for information from regulators.
"The ongoing investigation into this matter is continuing and we are fully cooperating with the FCA and other regulators", a bank representative said two weeks ago.
Last month, sources close to the case said that RBS had passed files of emails and instant messages sent to and by a former trader to the UK regulator, the Financial Conduct Authority.
The trader, Richard Usher, left RBS in 2010 and was reportedly suspended from his position as European head of currency spot trading at JPMorgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, head of European spot currency trading at Citi, was put on leave this week, while Matt Gardiner, senior currency trader at Barclays and UBS, was suspended by Standard Chartered this week.
None of these traders has been charged.
Mr. Usher's file included instant messages sent to and by bankers working at Barclays and Citigroup, sources close to the file said.
UBS explained this week that it had filed a lawsuit against some of its employees after the Swiss regulator, Finma, said it was investigating suspicions of currency market manipulation in a number of Swiss banks.
At least six authorities around the world - the European Commission, Finma, Swiss competition authority Weko, the FCA, the US Department of Justice and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority - are investigating allegations that bankers colluded to manipulate exchange rates.
HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Credit Suisse have also launched internal investigations or received requests for information from regulators, sources close to the matter said.
Banks have been sifting through instant messages and emails for years to find instances of wrongdoing.
News of these investigations has shaken traders in a sector that has been one of the biggest drivers of growth in investment bank trading units in recent years, but which has been challenged this year by low currency volatility that limits opportunities for speculators.
Some bankers have tried to downplay the matter by saying that it is almost impossible to manipulate the vast highly liquid foreign exchange market, but senior traders explain that this is not necessarily true.
A senior trader said that despite the high volume of daily foreign exchange trading, the fragmentation of liquidity between trading platforms and the increasing use of banks' own in-house platforms  explains why it is possible to start impacting the market at low cost .
The news comes on the same day that Credit Suisse announced it had fired a trader working in its London-based exchange-traded fund office this week after he caused a $6 million loss late last year.
The bank promptly informed the relevant authorities and cooperated with the regulators.
"We are convinced that the trader acted alone and that the matter was brought under control", said a representative of Credit Suisse.
