The energy is high, the rhythm is still fast.
There will be a break when Carol Prieur takes refuge under the dance mat, to deliver, microphone in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a part of Michaux's poem, monotone and monotone in the cry, and will continue dancing.
And the music to start again, and the sequence to resume.
This energetic, loud, and long-lasting burst of sound eventually deafens and numbs.
So does the regularity of the visual rhythm.
There are some beautiful flashes - the creation of images has always been a strength of Chouinard - like these hair that blur or these black fabrics that lengthen the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
It seems that the choreographer, instead of going to meet Michaux's work, has imposed itself, with its tics.
As a result, the bodies appear flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux's inks, like Gestalt forms, open up a wider and more exuberant imagination than the dance, more porous.
Only the ending, in negative, with its dancers hacked by a stroboscopic light and the white signs in a suddenly black theater, touches magic.
The audience loved it, the reception was warm.
Gymnopedias, after the intermission, is richer.
The stage is partly draped in grey, the dancers and a piano are covered in cloth, like furniture in a derelict house.
Dancers take turns playing the piano.
