This person will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, George Bwelle watched his sick father alternate periods of consciousness and unconsciousness and visit hospitals that were not equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaound√©, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he had only a broken arm, but he contracted an infection that spread to his brain, creating a hematoma that would haunt him for the rest of his life.
 There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon , said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him abroad if we had had enough money.
Instead, Dr. Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to crowded clinics and hospitals, getting him any treatment he could get.
"It's not easy", says Mr Bwelle.
You can leave your house at 5:00, you can run to the hospital to be the first, and you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
People can die waiting too long.
The situation has not changed much since the death of Dr. Bwelle's father in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor for every 5,000 people, according to the World Health Organization.
By comparison, the United States has a ratio of 1 doctor for every 413 people.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Cameroonians could not afford to pay for the consultation.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of the country's healthcare expenditure is in the private sector.
 The only problem they have is poverty , Dr Bwelle explained.
And because of poverty, they can't enjoy life.
After seeing his father and so many of his countrymen suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to change the course of events.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed over 700 free surgeries in the past year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at the Yaound√© Central Hospital.
And he started a nonprofit humanitarian organization, ASCOVIME, that goes to rural areas on weekends to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, with some 30 people, they crammed into vans with medical equipment on the roof and crossed difficult terrain to reach the villages that needed the most help.
Luck doesn't always follow them.
Many times they had to push the vehicles across rivers or muddy tracks.
But when they arrive, they are welcomed like heroes: the community throws a party, sings and dances, and offers them the best accommodations available.
In these villages, free healthcare is a good reason to celebrate, and Dr. Bwelle  with his big smile and overflowing energy  is more than happy to join the festivities.
The next morning, the team begins to receive hundreds of patients.
 We receive 500 people for each visit , said Mr Bwelle.
They live 40 miles from the village, and they come on foot.
In this mobile hospital, various health care services are provided.
Many are being treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites, and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others can get crutches, a pair of prescription glasses or a free birth certificate - a necessary document to go to school - but many poor families simply cannot afford to buy it.
In the evening, the team practices simple surgical procedures under local anesthesia.
The operations are usually carried out in a school, a town hall or a home; after the operation, the patient gets up and goes to the recovery room to give his place to the next person.
With the generator lighting, operating theatre lighting, and equipment sterilization, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers work into the early hours of Sunday morning.
It's a grueling rhythm, but the village musicians generally help keep the team motivated.
 They beat drums all night to keep us awake so we can keep working , Mr Bwelle explained.
On Sunday, the team returns to town, tired but proud of the work they've done.
The group, made up of Cameroonian doctors and medical students, has performed 700 free surgeries in the past year, and they know that their presence can make a difference to those they help.
One man explained that the free surgery he had to treat a hernia would allow him to work again.
"This will change my future and my family's future", the man said.
In addition to running this mobile hospital and working as a surgeon at the hospital, Dr. Bwelle also works at night in private medical offices around Yaound√©.
This second job, he explains, finances 60 percent of his association; the rest is covered by private donations.
"I don't know when he sleeps", said Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and a volunteer in Dr. Bwelle's group.
He's still in the hospital or trying to raise money for his charity so he can run these campaigns.
For medical students and nursing students like Katie O'Malley, who come from the United States and Europe to join Mr. Bwelle in his missions, it's a learning opportunity on the ground that they don't have at home.
 We were able to participate in operations to help swab the blood or pass the instruments to Dr. Bwelle , Ms. O'Malley explained.
This is not something you get a chance to do in America when you're a second-year medical student.
Student volunteers usually pay for their own journey to Cameroon, and often arrive with collected medical supplies.
But once in Yaound√©, their board, transportation and education are taken care of by Dr. Bwelle.
"He is a hero, there is no doubt about it", said Katie O'Malley.
He has given his life to this association, and his desire to help the Cameroonian people is not going to die.
Dr Bwelle does not find the relatively constant workload a problem.
Helping others to live a happy life in fulfillment of the promise he made to his Father is something that brings him immense joy.
 I am so happy when I do this job , added Mr Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
Making people laugh and relieving pain are the reasons I do this.
