John Kerry has admitted, in an unprecedented move, that US intelligence has gone too far in an inappropriate way.
John Kerry has indicated a softening of the US defensive stance towards its surveillance programs by admitting, unprecedentedly, that on several occasions the spying had gone too far in inappropriate ways.
The Secretary of State also admitted that he, like Barack Obama, had been operating on "automatic pilot" when a series of incendiary revelations by whistleblower Edward Snowden about the NSA's spying activities came to light.
The leaks have put the U.S. government at the center of a diplomatic storm with its allies.
Speaking at an intergovernmental conference in London via video link, Mr Kerry said: 'It is undeniable that the President, myself and other members of the government have been taking things on autopilot because we had the opportunity to do so, from the Second World War to the difficult years of the Cold War, and then of course on 9/11.
He later became the first senior member of the United States government to admit that American espionage had gone too far, but insisted that the rights of everyone had not been violated.
He said:  In some cases it went too far in inappropriate ways. 
And the president is determined to try to clarify and make it clear to people that he was now making a thorough review of these practices so that no one would feel deceived.
I can assure you that innocent people will not be abused in this process.
Mr. Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was a force for good and that its surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added:  We live in a new world where people are ready to blow themselves up. 
There is a radical extremism in the world that is determined to try to kill people, blow up and attack governments.
What if you could intercept their communications and stop them before they act?
We have indeed prevented airplanes from crashing, buildings from exploding, and people from being murdered because we have been able to learn the facts in advance.
In the meantime, US lawmakers will travel to Europe to address concerns about the alleged US spying case and convince Europeans of the need to continue joint counter-terrorism efforts with the US, the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said on Thursday.
Senator Chris Murphy of Connecticut said that he had spoken to members of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about the threats they had made about a possible withdrawal of counter-terrorism organizations because of the sense of frustration that the National Security Agency's surveillance is generating.
 It is really important for the protection of national security in the United States that the Europeans remain by our side in the mutual commitment to fight terrorism , said Murphy, a first-term Democrat and chair of the US Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs, in an interview from Washington.
And I'm going to Europe to make it clear that we must continue to work together to fight terrorism, despite the anger that NSA's programs have caused.
The press reports that the NSA has intercepted millions of communications in Europe, which has strained relations with some US allies, however the agency's director said this week that this was inaccurate and that it was a misunderstanding because it concerned metadata that NATO allies had collected and shared with the US.
Other revelations have included documents leaked by Snowden that claim the NSA intercepted data and communications from the cell phones of German Chancellor Angela Merkel and 34 other heads of state.
Director of Intelligence James Clapper justified the Allied spying by stating that it was necessary and common practice on both sides.
In this atmosphere of turmoil, Murphy indicated that his office was organizing a congressional trip, which was expected to take place this year, and that he hoped the delegation would include members of both parties and both houses.
The names of the other participating legislators are expected to be released in the coming days.
He said the route was still to be worked out.
Murphy stated that the purpose of the trip was to improve relations, but also to demonstrate  affectionate firmness.
He said that European heads of state should be honest with their citizens about the type of spying programmes they themselves have been applying for years.
 We can change our surveillance programmes to better protect the rights of Europeans, but they also need to understand that we are not the only ones in the world spying,  said Murphy.
Meanwhile, Mr. Kerry is scheduled to travel this weekend to the Middle East and Poland to address the resentment over US policies in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as US surveillance activities.
