Australian woman appeals from prison sentence in Thailand
A 21-year-old Sydney resident, who was sentenced to 15 days in Phuket for falsely claiming that she was assaulted by a taxi driver, has appealed the verdict and been released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was initially found guilty by a Phuket Provincial Court on June 15 of making false statements after she told Thai police that a local taxi driver, accompanied by two other men who were holding her, had assaulted her early on Sunday, June 10.
However, CCTV footage later revealed that she had safely returned to her hotel after separating from her Australian boyfriend.
Phuket police questioned Bamford for two days before she confessed to making up the whole story.
She was held in a cell at the local police station before the court hearing.
Bamford was sentenced to 15 days in a low-security detention centre on the outskirts of Phuket rather than a women's prison.
She is the daughter of former Australian Rugby League player Peter Tunks, who appealed to the Canberra Ministry of Foreign Affairs to help his daughter.
Tunks told the Sydney Sunday Telegraph that the entire family was "extremely concerned" about her daughter's well-being and wanted her to return to Australia.
"We have obviously had a distressing time, but we hope to get her home safely as soon as possible", said Tunks.
Bamford appealed the verdict and was released on 50,000 baht bail.
In Australia, the press said that in the meantime, she was on holiday in the Krabi region, south of Thailand.
Thai judicial sources said Bamford was represented by a local Phuket lawyer, but warned that the appeal could lead to a sentence of up to two years in prison and incarceration in an adult prison.
However, after the recent murder of Australian travel agent Michelle Smith in Phuket, Thailand may also be looking to repair its damaged image with tourists, which could lead to a acquittal.
